]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em; list-style-type: decimal;">\n<ol class="references">\n<li id="cite_note-1"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">"Para los autores \xc3\xa1rabes medievales, el t\xc3\xa9rmino Al-Andalus designa la totalidad de las zonas conquistadas&#160;\xe2\x80\x94 siquiera temporalmente&#160;\xe2\x80\x94 por tropas arabo-musulmanas en territorios actualmente pertenecientes a Portugal, Espa\xc3\xb1a y Francia" ("For medieval Arab authors, Al-Andalus designated all the conquered areas&#160;\xe2\x80\x94 even temporarily&#160;\xe2\x80\x94by Arab-Muslim troops in territories now belonging to Portugal, Spain and France"), <a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos%C3%A9_%C3%81ngel_Garc%C3%ADa_de_Cort%C3%A1zar" class="extiw" title="es:Jos\xc3\xa9 \xc3\x81ngel Garc\xc3\xada de Cort\xc3\xa1zar">Jos\xc3\xa9 \xc3\x81ngel Garc\xc3\xada de Cort\xc3\xa1zar</a>, <i>V Semana de Estudios Medievales: N\xc3\xa1jera, 1 al 5 de agosto de 1994</i>, Gobierno de La Rioja, Instituto de Estudios Riojanos, 1995, p.52.</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Ruano.28Spain.292002-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Ruano.28Spain.292002_2-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book"><a href="https://es.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eloy_Benito_Ruano" class="extiw" title="es:Eloy Benito Ruano">Eloy Benito Ruano</a> (2002). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=xX35wGGJaaIC"><i>T\xc3\xb3picos y realidades de la Edad Media</i></a>. Real Academia de la Historia. p.&#160;79. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-84-95983-06-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-84-95983-06-0">978-84-95983-06-0</a>. <q>"Los arabes y musulmanes de la Edad Media aplicaron el nombre de Al-Andalus a todas aquellas tierras que habian formado parte del reino visigodo: la Peninsula Ib\xc3\xa9rica y la Septimania ultrapirenaica." ("The Arabs and Muslims from the Middle Ages used the name of al-Andalus for all those lands that were formerly part of the Visigothic kingdom: the Iberian Peninsula and Septimania")</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.au=Eloy+Benito+Ruano&amp;rft.btitle=T%C3%B3picos+y+realidades+de+la+Edad+Media&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-84-95983-06-0&amp;rft.pages=79&amp;rft.pub=Real+Academia+de+la+Historia&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DxX35wGGJaaIC&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Esposito, John L (2003). <i>Oxford Dictionary of Islam</i>. Oxford University Press.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.aufirst=John+L&amp;rft.aulast=Esposito&amp;rft.btitle=Oxford+Dictionary+of+Islam&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.pub=Oxford+University+Press&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="/w/index.php?title=Joseph_F._O%27Callaghan&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Joseph F. O\'Callaghan (page does not exist)">Joseph F. O\'Callaghan</a>, <i>A History of Medieval Spain</i>, Cornell University Press, 1983, p.142</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Lewis, Bernard. The Jews of Islam. PrincetMeyrick, Fredrick. The Doctrine of the Church of England on the Holy Communion.on, NJ: Princeton University Press, 1984.pg. 14. "Under the ruling Caliph (the descendant of Mohammed--the prophet of G-d on earth), the Jews were able to preserve their rites and traditions. Peaceful coexistence led to their economic and social expansion. Their status was that of <a href="/wiki/Dhimmis" class="mw-redirect" title="Dhimmis">Dhimmis</a>, non-Muslims living in a land governed by Muslims. The Jews had limited autonomy, but full rights to practice their religion, as well as full protection by their Muslim rulers, but this did not occur for free. There was a specific tax called the jizya that Dhimmis had to pay to receive these benefits. Having its origin in the Qur\'an, it states Dhimmis who did not pay this tax, should either convert to Islam, or face the death penalty (Qur\'an 9, 29). This tax, higher than the tax Muslims had to pay, was in several occasions one of the most important sources of income for the kingdom. The jizya was not only a tax, but also a symbolic expression of subordination (Lewis 14)."It is a common misapprehension that the holy war meant that the Muslims gave their opponents a choice \'between Islam and the sword\'. This was sometimes the case, but only when the opponents were polytheist and idol-worshippers. For Jews, Christians, and other \'People of the Book\', there was a third possibility, they might become a \'protected group\', paying a tax or tribute to the Muslims but enjoying internal autonomy" (Watt 144)</span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20151208095542/http://www.elhistoriador.com.ar/aula/medieval/reconquista_espanola.php">"Historia en el aula"</a>. El Historiador. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.elhistoriador.com.ar/aula/medieval/reconquista_espanola.php">the original</a> on 8 December 2015<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">28 November</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.btitle=Historia+en+el+aula&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=El+Historiador&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.elhistoriador.com.ar%2Faula%2Fmedieval%2Freconquista_espanola.php&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-7"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation web"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.andalucia.com/history/spainsmoorishhistory.htm">"The Moors in Andalucia - 8th to 15th Centuries"</a>. Andalucia Com SL<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">28 November</span> 2015</span>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.btitle=The+Moors+in+Andalucia+-+8th+to+15th+Centuries&amp;rft.genre=unknown&amp;rft.pub=Andalucia+Com+SL&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.andalucia.com%2Fhistory%2Fspainsmoorishhistory.htm&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-MMOA-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-MMOA_8-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Michael L. Bates (1992). "The Islamic Coinage of Spain". In Jerrilynn D. Dodds. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=lLAryx8bC8UC&amp;pg=PA384"><i>Al-Andalus: The Art of Islamic Spain</i></a>. Metropolitan Museum of Art. p.&#160;384. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-87099-636-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-87099-636-8">978-0-87099-636-8</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.atitle=The+Islamic+Coinage+of+Spain&amp;rft.au=Michael+L.+Bates&amp;rft.btitle=Al-Andalus%3A+The+Art+of+Islamic+Spain&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-87099-636-8&amp;rft.pages=384&amp;rft.pub=Metropolitan+Museum+of+Art&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DlLAryx8bC8UC%26pg%3DPA384&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Glick2005-9"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Glick2005_9-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Thomas F. Glick (2005). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=cWqmebvcjj0C&amp;pg=PR21"><i>Islamic And Christian Spain in the Early Middle Ages</i></a>. BRILL. p.&#160;21. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/90-04-14771-3" title="Special:BookSources/90-04-14771-3">90-04-14771-3</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.au=Thomas+F.+Glick&amp;rft.btitle=Islamic+And+Christian+Spain+in+the+Early+Middle+Ages&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=90-04-14771-3&amp;rft.pages=21&amp;rft.pub=BRILL&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DcWqmebvcjj0C%26pg%3DPR21&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Vallv.C3.A91986-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Vallv.C3.A91986_10-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Joaqu\xc3\xadn Vallv\xc3\xa9 (1986). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=9p0cAAAAMAAJ"><i>La divisi\xc3\xb3n territorial de la Espa\xc3\xb1a musulmana</i></a>. Instituto de Filolog\xc3\xada. pp.&#160;55\xe2\x80\x9359. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-84-00-06295-8" title="Special:BookSources/978-84-00-06295-8">978-84-00-06295-8</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.au=Joaqu%C3%ADn+Vallv%C3%A9&amp;rft.btitle=La+divisi%C3%B3n+territorial+de+la+Espa%C3%B1a+musulmana&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-84-00-06295-8&amp;rft.pages=55-59&amp;rft.pub=Instituto+de+Filolog%C3%ADa&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3D9p0cAAAAMAAJ&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Halm1989-11"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Halm1989_11-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Halm, Heinz (1989). "Al-Andalus und Gothica Sors". <i>Der Islam</i>. <b>66</b> (2): 252\xe2\x80\x93263. <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//doi.org/10.1515%2Fislm.1989.66.2.252">10.1515/islm.1989.66.2.252</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.atitle=Al-Andalus+und+Gothica+Sors&amp;rft.aufirst=Heinz&amp;rft.aulast=Halm&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.jtitle=Der+Islam&amp;rft.pages=252-263&amp;rft.volume=66&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1515%2Fislm.1989.66.2.252&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Bossong2002-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Bossong2002_12-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation journal">Bossong, Georg (2002). Restle, David; Zaefferer, Dietmar, eds. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://web.archive.org/web/20080627064440/http://www.rose.unizh.ch/seminar/personen/bossong/boss_bask_120.pdf">"Der Name al-Andalus: neue \xc3\x9cberlegungen zu einem alten Problem"</a> [The Name al-Andalus: Revisiting an Old Problem] <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span>. <i>Trends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs</i>. Sounds and systems: studies in structure and change. (in German). Berlin: De Gruyter Mouton. <b>141</b>: 149. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number" title="International Standard Serial Number">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//www.worldcat.org/issn/1861-4302">1861-4302</a>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.rose.unizh.ch/seminar/personen/bossong/boss_bask_120.pdf">the original</a> <span style="font-size:85%;">(PDF)</span> on June 27, 2008<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved <span class="nowrap">8 September</span> 2013</span>. <q>Only a few years after the Islamic conquest of Spain, <i>Al-Andalus</i> appears in coin inscriptions as the Arabic equivalent of <i>Hispania</i>. The traditionally held view that the etymology of this name has to do with the Vandals is shown to have no serious foundation. The phonetic, morphosyntactic, and also historical problems connected with this etymology are too numerous. Moreover, the existence of this name in various parts of central and northern Spain proves that <i>Al-Andalus</i> cannot be derived from this <a href="/wiki/Germanic_peoples" title="Germanic peoples">Germanic tribe</a>. It was the original name of the Punta Marroqu\xc3\xad cape near Tarifa; very soon, it became generalized to designate the whole Peninsula. Undoubtedly, the name is of Pre-Indo-European origin. The parts of this compound (<i>anda</i> and <i>luz</i>) are frequent in the indigenous toponymy of the Iberian Peninsula.</q></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.atitle=Der+Name+al-Andalus%3A+neue+%C3%9Cberlegungen+zu+einem+alten+Problem&amp;rft.aufirst=Georg&amp;rft.aulast=Bossong&amp;rft.date=2002&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.issn=1861-4302&amp;rft.jtitle=Trends+in+Linguistics.+Studies+and+Monographs&amp;rft.pages=149&amp;rft.volume=141&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rose.unizh.ch%2Fseminar%2Fpersonen%2Fbossong%2Fboss_bask_120.pdf&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Collins2012-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Collins2012_13-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Roger Collins (7 May 2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=AVBzo8Vak7sC&amp;pg=PA12"><i>Caliphs and Kings: Spain, 796-1031</i></a>. John Wiley &amp; Sons. pp.&#160;8\xe2\x80\x939. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-631-18184-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-631-18184-2">978-0-631-18184-2</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.au=Roger+Collins&amp;rft.btitle=Caliphs+and+Kings%3A+Spain%2C+796-1031&amp;rft.date=2012-05-07&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-631-18184-2&amp;rft.pages=8-9&amp;rft.pub=John+Wiley+%26+Sons&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DAVBzo8Vak7sC%26pg%3DPA12&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-.E1.B9.AC.C4.81ha2016-14"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-.E1.B9.AC.C4.81ha2016_14-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">\'Abdulw\xc4\x81hid D\xe1\xb8\xa5an\xc5\xabn \xe1\xb9\xac\xc4\x81ha (July 2016). "Early Muslim Settlement in Spain: The Berber Tribes in Al-Andalus". <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=RCglDwAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA166"><i>Routledge Library Editions: Muslim Spain</i></a>. Taylor &amp; Francis. pp.&#160;166\xe2\x80\x93177. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-1-134-98576-0" title="Special:BookSources/978-1-134-98576-0">978-1-134-98576-0</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.atitle=Early+Muslim+Settlement+in+Spain%3A+The+Berber+Tribes+in+Al-Andalus&amp;rft.au=%27Abdulw%C4%81hid+D%E1%B8%A5an%C5%ABn+%E1%B9%AC%C4%81ha&amp;rft.btitle=Routledge+Library+Editions%3A+Muslim+Spain&amp;rft.date=2016-07&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.isbn=978-1-134-98576-0&amp;rft.pages=166-177&amp;rft.pub=Taylor+%26+Francis&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DRCglDwAAQBAJ%26pg%3DPA166&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-15"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Specifically, 27,000 Syrian troops were composed of 6,000 men from each of the four main Syrian <i>junds</i> of <a href="/wiki/Jund_Dimashq" title="Jund Dimashq">Jund Dimashq (Damascus)</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jund_Hims" title="Jund Hims">Jund Hims (Homs)</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jund_al-Urdunn" title="Jund al-Urdunn">Jund al-Urdunn (Jordan)</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Jund_Filastin" title="Jund Filastin">Jund Filastin (Filastin)</a>, plus 3,000 from <a href="/wiki/Jund_Qinnasrin" title="Jund Qinnasrin">Jund Qinnasrin</a>. An additional 3,000 were picked up in <a href="/wiki/Egypt" title="Egypt">Egypt</a>. See R. Dozy (1913) <i>Spanish Islam: A History of the Muslims in Spain</i> (translated by Francis Griffin Stokes from the Spanish <i>Histoire de Musulmans d\'Espagne</i>) Chatto &amp; Windus, London, <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=AtQ7yAftTdQC&amp;pg=PA133">page 133</a></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Collins201212-16"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Collins201212_16-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Roger Collins (7 May 2012). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=AVBzo8Vak7sC&amp;pg=PA12"><i>Caliphs and Kings: Spain, 796-1031</i></a>. John Wiley &amp; Sons. p.&#160;12. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-631-18184-2" title="Special:BookSources/978-0-631-18184-2">978-0-631-18184-2</a>.</cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AAl-Andalus&amp;rft.au=Roger+Collins&amp;rft.btitle=Caliphs+and+Kings%3A+Spain%2C+796-1031&amp;rft.date=2012-05-07&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-631-18184-2&amp;rft.pages=12&amp;rft.pub=John+Wiley+%26+Sons&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DAVBzo8Vak7sC%26pg%3DPA12&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>\n<li id="cite_note-Makki1992-17"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Makki1992_17-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite class="citation book">Mahmoud Makki (1992). "The Political History of Al-Andalus". In Salma Khadra Jayyusi, Manuela Mar\xc3\xadn. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://books.google.com/books?id=cbfORLWv1HkC&amp;pg=PA12"><i>The Legacy of Muslim Spain</i></a>. BRILL. pp.&#160;12\xe2\x80\x9313. <a